%N A390368 Triangle read by rows: number of permutations of length n that require exactly k removals from the beginning to become heapable.
%C A390368 A permutation of 1..n is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A390368 For a permutation p=(p(1),...,p(n)), define m(p) = the minimum number of initial elements that must be removed so that the truncated permutation is heapable.
%C A390368 This sequence gives the distribution of m(p) over all n! permutations of length n.
